title: ion-alert
body: An Alert is a dialog that presents users with information or collects information from the user using inputs. An alert appears on top of the app's content, and must be manually dismissed by the user before they can resume interaction with the app. It can also optionally have a

Alerts can also include several different inputs whose data can be passed back to the app. Inputs can be used as a simple way to prompt users for information. Radios, checkboxes and text inputs are all accepted, but they cannot be mixed. For example, an alert could have all radio button inputs, or all checkbox inputs, but the same alert cannot mix radio and checkbox inputs. Do note however, different types of "text" inputs can be mixed, such as
etc. If you require a complex form UI which doesn't fit within the guidelines of an alert then we recommend building the form within a modal instead.

In Angular, the CSS of a specific page is scoped only to elements of that page. Even though the Alert can be presented from within a page, the
element is appended outside of the current page. This means that any custom styles need to go in a global stylesheet file. In an Ionic Angular starter this can be the

props.name: backdropDismiss
props.docs: If true, the alert will be dismissed when the backdrop is clicked.

props.name: buttons
props.docs: Array of buttons to be added to the alert.

props.name: cssClass
props.docs: Additional classes to apply for custom CSS. If multiple classes are provided they should be separated by spaces.

props.name: enterAnimation
props.docs: Animation to use when the alert is presented.

props.name: header
props.docs: The main title in the heading of the alert.

props.name: inputs
props.docs: Array of input to show in the alert.

props.name: keyboardClose
props.docs: If true, the keyboard will be automatically dismissed when the overlay is presented.

props.name: leaveAnimation
props.docs: Animation to use when the alert is dismissed.

props.name: message
props.docs:
The main message to be displayed in the alert. message can accept either plaintext or HTML as a string. To display characters normally reserved for HTML, they must be escaped. For example <Ionic> would become <Ionic>

For more information: Security Documentation

props.name: mode
props.docs: The mode determines which platform styles to use.

props.name: subHeader
props.docs: The subtitle in the heading of the alert. Displayed under the title.

props.name: translucent
props.docs: If true, the alert will be translucent. Only applies when the mode is "ios" and the device supports backdrop-filter.

methods.name: dismiss
methods.signature: dismiss(data?: any, role?: string | undefined) => Promise<boolean>
methods.docs: Dismiss the alert overlay after it has been presented.

docsTags.name: param
docsTags.text: data Any data to emit in the dismiss events.

docsTags.name: param
docsTags.text:
role The role of the element that is dismissing the alert.
This can be useful in a button handler for determining which button was
clicked to dismiss the alert.
Some examples include: ``"cancel"`, `"destructive"`, "selected"`, and `"backdrop"`.

methods.name: onDidDismiss
methods.docs: Returns a promise that resolves when the alert did dismiss.

methods.name: onWillDismiss
methods.docs: Returns a promise that resolves when the alert will dismiss.

methods.name: present
methods.docs: Present the alert overlay after it has been created.

docs: An Alert is a dialog that presents users with information or collects information from the user using inputs. An alert appears on top of the app's content, and must be manually dismissed by the user before they can resume interaction with the app. It can also optionally have a `header`, `subHeader` and `message`.
